\sub חקה ,חֻקָּה ,הקק
\intro From the verb הקק, which means to inscribe on a hard surface, or to decree, it refers to an authoritarian decree, or law, most often with the sense of permanence:1. a permanent and binding law, an enduring custom, prescribed by God or by a person in authority.3. a fixed and permanent allotment, or provision for designated individuals decreed by God or by a person in authority.4. a person's lot in life as decreed by God, whether it is fate or the fulfilment of a promise.5. the natural order and boundaries of the universe as set by GodThe most frequent context of this word is the Mosaic Law, especially in reference to laws and special allotments for the priests.The sense of permanence is re-inforced in a number of instances by the qualifying word 'OLAM (lasting) as in ----, and also in reference to natural boundaries and laws set by God.  When referring to legislation, the term חֹק is used to highlight the permanence of the laws. In the case of prescribed duties for servants (Sense 1, context h), however, the sense of permanence seems to be less prevalent; here חֹק seems to focus more on the sense of a fixed set of tasks for the day.
\altint A couple of passages have been glossed by HALOT as 'a prescribed task' : Exo 5:14, Pro 31:15. Both of these are interpreted here as |ia prescribed portion. |i*Aside from these two references, there is no other evidence that that XOQ should have this meaning. In both cases, the sense of '|ia prescribed amount to be alloted to an individual|i*' can be interpreted. |i |i*In the Exodus passage, the provision of the required allotment of bricks does indeed involve a required task. However, the Proverbs passage can be interpreted as a portion of food to be given to the female servants for their needs, rather than the notion of daily tasks assigned to them.
\comp 31x in the Psalms of which 22 in Psalm 119; 21x in DeuteronomyAll of the senses of חֹק involve 1) the domain of authoritarian action or decree, and 2) the sense of permanence or regularity. In Meaning 1, the recipient of the חֹק is required to perform certain actions. In Meaning 2, the beneficiary of the חֹק is the one who receives an allotment that is designated for him specifically. The third and fourth senses consist of an authoritarian action on the part of God that concern the lot of humans (Meaning 3), and the limits and laws of nature (Meaning 4).The paired expression: XOQ VE MISHPAT merits some attention, as it is variously translated. It can also be found in plural form. There seems to be a question as to whether it should be translated as a semantic unit ('fixed rule' NJPS), or as two separate items ('decrees and laws' NIV)
\dfnotes 1. The feminine form of XOQ, XUQQAH semantically overlaps with XOQ; however there is a different distribution of usage. a. XOQ is found more in reference to non-specified laws, while XUQQAH seems to be preferred in the context of specific laws. However, both terms can be found in both contexts. b. XOQ refers to the permanence of laws, while XUQQAH seems to focus more on the feature of repetition of laws and customs.  Thus, XUQQAH is used more frequently to refer to customs and traditions of other peoples.c. In the context of natural laws, XOQ refers more to the limits and order of nature, while XUQQAH refers to the repetitious acts of nature. 2. See MISHPAT, ''EDUT, MITSWAH, TORAH - note that these terms do not distinguish different types of laws. Rather they different aspects of the law - Mishpat - a judgment,  mitswah - a command, torah - direction, xoq - permanently established. Each one has a semantic field that overlaps with the other.
