\intro Since understanding of how ‘success’ comes about is culturally conditioned, the translation of צלח (‘be successful’) is likely to differ from language to language. In some it may be best expressed by the condition for success - ‘ability’ in some way; in others it may be best expressed by the outcome, such as an expression which covers ‘victory’. Since in scripture success (or lack of success) is divinely influenced, and also influenced by moral choices, the words chosen to translate ‘success’ should be able to carry these notions, rather than, for instance, to imply the possession of magical power.The frame of ‘success’ with respect to people requires: (i) a person who experiences or achieves the success; (ii) one of more events in which this person is successful (iii); a measure or way of distinguishing success from failure. While the first of these elements is always expressed in the Hebrew text, the other two may be unexpressed, to be inferred from the context. The extent to which this is acceptable in the language into which translation is being made will have to be determined; one or both of these elements may need to be made more explicit.It is likely that the concept of ‘success’ will need to be translated differently in one or more of the several domains that occur in scripture: Personal Welfare, Warfare (where ‘victory’ may be an appropriate translation), Land/Nation, Venture, God’s Purposes, Justice, Objects (see below). There is some overlapping of these domains.In the domain of ‘objects’ (which extends ‘success’ beyond the frame used by English speakers), a different word may need to be used to translate ‘success’ than is used for the other domains. This composite domain of ‘objects’ collects together three instances: ‘belt’, ‘vine’ and ‘wood of vine’ (in the NIV and NLT, for instance, ‘thrive’ is used in the context of ‘vine’.)The grammatical subject of the Hebrew verb expressing ‘success’ may be the person or people seeking success, the activity in which success takes place or is being sought (e.g. Num 14:41), or an object used by the person or people seeking success (e.g. Isa 54:17).In scripture, the frame of ‘success’ is found in a positive sub-frame (obeying God results in success, e.g. Jos 1:8), a negative sub-frame (disobeying God results in failure, e.g. Deu 28:29), and in what could be called a contrary sub-frame (evil men sometimes are successful, e.g. Psa 37:7), which gains its force of meaning from the normality of the other two sub-frames.
\hebraist The verb צלח may occur either in the qal form or the hiphil form. The hiphil form may or may not have a causative meaning. Whether the hiphil form takes on causative meaning or not is determined by the context.One issue that can be discussed is whether there is a distinction between the qal and the hiphil forms of this verb. Of the 55 usages of this Hebrew verb which refer to ‘success’ in the canonical Old Testament, the qal form is used 15 times and the hiphil form 40 times. Of these 40 uses, in some 30 of these instances the hiphil form is clearly used without causative meaning, that is to say only one agent is expressed; there are only about 10 instances of its use with clear causative meaning, that is to say two agents being expressed, one causing the other to be successful. All instances where the expressed grammatical subject is a thing, that is non-human, involve use of the qal form.One might surmise from this that the qal form is used where the subject is seen as less agentive. In other words that the hiphil form, even when only one agent is involved, is more agentive in some way (that is to say, the agent is seen more as causing himself to be successful.) We have labelled this role as agent/patient since the participant is always involved both in causing his success in some way and in experiencing it. However it does not seem possible to prove whether this distinction of agency (qal = less agentive, hiphil = more agentive, even when not causative) is correct. Western versions do not attempt to make such a distinction in their translations. In languages where degree of agency is marked, such a distinction might appear in translation. However, since the distinction cannot be proven, it is probably best in such languages to read agency out of the context rather than depend on a qal/hiphil distinction which cannot be substantiated.In two cases - Jdg 18:5 and Psa 1:3 - the hiphil form could potentially be analysed as causative (with God as causing agent), or with the activity (‘our road’, ‘all that he does’) as the grammatical subject. A causative analysis does not seem plausible in either case. In the first case the verb is clearly marked as having a feminine subject. In both cases (as additional evidence) the Septuagint translators understood the activity to be the subject.
\altint With respect to the plural verb ‘success’ in Jer 5:28, one question concerns who should be taken as the grammatical subject, whether the ‘wicked men’ of verse 26 or the ‘fatherless’ of this verse. Most modern translations render the clause as a purpose clause (c.f. Waltke and O’Connor 1990:650.) If the subject is taken as ‘wicked men’ it could be rendered (RSV) ‘they [wicked men] judge not with justice the cause of the fatherless, to make it prosper’, or (NIV) ‘they do not plead the case of the fatherless to win it’. If the subject is taken as the ‘fatherless’ it could be rendered: ‘that they [the fatherless] may have success’.Tawil (Tawil 1976) argues from a related language that the verb in this context should be understood as ‘provide/render justice’ and, claiming implicit negation from the context, translates the verse (with ‘wicked men’ as subject): ‘they judge not the cause, the cause of the orphan they do not justly render’.Although these three interpretations differ in detail, they are concordant as regards the resultant meaning. Tawil’s interpretation is more radical, since it involves the detail of an extended meaning for צלח (‘provide/render justice’) and the need to adopt an implied negative; the resultant meaning in the context of the preceding and following clause is, nevertheless, the same.A fourth more literal possibility is represented by the Segond Révisé translation, but is more disjointed: ‘ils ne défendent pas la cause, la cause de l'orphelin, et ils prospèrent; ils ne font pas droit aux pauvres’/’they do not defend the cause, the cause of the orphan, and they prosper; they do not defend the right of the poor’. This disjointedness suggests that an original speaker/hearer would have understood the expression in a more meaningful way, however we lack sufficient access to original speaker/hearer knowledge to know what that would have been.If a grammatical subject or object has to be supplied, a compromise is to use ‘cause/case’ as the subject or object and render the clause as a purpose clause, as in the first two options presented above.
\dfnotes The domains of success that appear in scripture overlap to some extent. The personal success or welfare of the king, for instance, will affect the welfare of the land or nation.The frame of ‘success’ requires: (i) a person (or, in the Hebrew frame, a thing) who achieves and experiences the success; (ii) one of more events in which this person is successful (iii); a measure or way of distinguishing success from failure. (This last could also be thought of as the ideal version of (ii), that is to say a successful version of the event or events.) The first of these elements will be expressed in the Hebrew text, but the other two may be unexpressed, to be inferred from the context. The extent to which this is acceptable in the language into which translation is being done will have to be determined; one or both of these elements may need to be made more explicit. There may also be other participants, specifically agents; such as a ‘causing agent’ who causes the events to be successful (always Divine); and in one case (Jer 2:37) a ‘secondary’ or ‘helping agent’.In scripture, the frame of ‘success’ is found in a positive form (obeying God results in success, e.g. Jos 1:8), a negative form (disobeying God results in failure, e.g. Deu 28:29), and in what could be called a contrary form (evil men are sometimes successful, e.g. Psa 37:7), which gains its force of its meaning from the normality of the other two forms.The inclusion of objects in the frame of ‘successfulness’ for the Hebrew language means that this frame is conceptually larger than the corresponding frame in English. It includes notions of ‘effectiveness’ and ‘productiveness’ (and these could be considered supplementary names for this frame.)
