\intro עת appears to have a single basic meaning of a short period of (or point in) time (or, for a more distant time, perhaps a longer period of time). By virtue of this very bland meaning עת is normally found in association with a word or phrase denoting an event or situation (if a word, in the analysis below we have referred to it as the 'specifying term'). עת can also be found with indexicals ('this', 'that') and is used to relate one event to another in a discourse.An important question is whether the ANE notion of time was similar to our own, that is to say whether it was a 'scientific' notion of time, in which a uniform notion of linear time is a primary and independent concept. Of course, we also have our own 'folk' notion of time. More likely: (1) events or situations were seen as more primary; (2) many events recurred; (3) events were considered to be controlled or brought about in some way (including recurrent ones) - the 'world-of-the-Gods' was involved in controlling them, possibly in reaction of the actions of man. (4) As a consequence, we can probably claim ANE time was not an primary independent uniform abstract concept, but, in a more subsidiary fashion, part of the way of referring to events and situations, for instance the termination of a bad (for example, oppressive) situation, or the arrival in the future of a good (for example, righteous and lasting) situation. Evidence for this is that עת, as noted above, rarely occurs by itself. Where עת does occur by itself, it is often elliptical.
\comp there are grammatical differences in the use of 'time': (1) sentence (paragraph) initial - though this is also adverbial, it serves to help 'structure' the discourse; (2) as a conjunction which may be translated by 'when' - though also adverbial in form; (3) in a nominal phrase; (4) in other adverbial phrases - these may also serve to relate events (these differences should be noted in the analysis that follows, so that they are not ignored or confused)
