\sub גּוֹלָה, גָּלוּת, גִּלָּיוֹן
\intro This verb either means 'to go into exile' or 'to reveal'. As I have analysed it, this verb has seven main meanings - 1. To go into exile. 2. To carry or be carried into exile 3. To depart 4. To be carried away. 5. To wither and disppear. 6. To be removed.  7. To reveal, or uncover (as yet uncompiled).Meaning two implies an agent, whether explict or not. There are  many cases where the LORD is the agent ie the one causing the people to be deported and have to live in exile in a foreign country e.g. 2Ki 17:11, 1Ch 5:41; Jer 29:7, 14; (Lam 4:22;) Ezk 39:28 and Amo 5:27. See also 1Ch 5:26 where Yahweh stirs up the spirit of two Assyrian kings to take several tribes from Israel into exile, and Amo 1:6 where he promises to punish those (‘Gaza’ i.e. Philistines?) who sold captives from Israel to Edom.
\tnotes Note the two main senses: 'to go into exile' and 'to reveal' . Within the first main sense the various contextual uses of the verb can be broken up by use of frames. The most frequently occurring frame is 'exile' but others also occur.
\hebraist The two homonyms are mainly split by the roots of the verb (1. Niphal? Hiphil and Hophal respectively vs. 2. Piel, Pual, and Hithpolel respectively). The Qal, however, can mean either. Roughly half the Qal, and all the Hiphil, (Niphal?) and Hophal forms of this verb are used with the sense of 'to depart' (into exile).
\altint NIDOTTE suggests that the word has a core meaning of 'to uncover', but the evidence for this is unconvincing.
\addinfo Some general notes on the exile follow here. It means to go or be taken from your homeland into a foreign country by an invading power. This is often referred to by the term 'exile', but is really a mass deportation, as still happens occasionally in modern times (eg Stalin's deportation of some minority groups from Russia to Central Asia).|b |b*To understand the exile from a biblical perspective one must first read about God's covenant with his people Israel in the book of Deuteronomy. In that book they are promised many blessings if they obey God, and curses if they do not (Deu 11:26). If they obey God, they will remain in the land which they have yet to conquer, but has been promised to them. If they disobey God they will be removed from the land (Deu 28:63). The term גלה does not occur until the historical books, where it is reported that the Israelites did disobey God, and so they were sent into exile (2Ki 17:23). By this time the kingdom was split into two, the Northern kingdom was exiled to Assyria, and much later the Southern kingdom was exiled to Babylon. The actual dates are 734 and 722 BC for Israel, and 597 and 586 BC for Judah. Of course it did not end there, as some from Israel remained in the North and intermarried with other peoples (to form the Samaritans?), and some in the South remained in Judah at the time of their exile. But the books of Ezra and Nehemiah tell us how a group of believers came back to Jerusalem in Judah and began rebuilding the city walls and the temple. They found that those who had remained in the land had mostly intermarried with the surrounding peoples.
