\intro 1. The primary meaning of |hשַׁחַת|h* is a hole in the ground which is used for a trap.2. Used metaphorically, |hשַׁחַת|h* means the underworld, a place no one can leave, so a kind of trap. 3. When used metaphorically, the concept of the underworld is often a metonomy for death. Either the word itself or a whole phrase such as |hתִּקְרַב לַשַּׁחַת|h* 'it drew near to |hשַׁחַת|h*' can be the metonomy.
\tnotes The netherworld, the place of the dead, was seen as underground by the Hebews. It is not the same as the grave where dead bodies are put. It is also not a place of punishment, so words like 'hell' where punishment in the underworld takes place are not appropriate.All the words for underworld are used metaphorically to refer to the event of death. |hשַׁחַת|h* is used often with the words |hחַיָּה|h*  (life) and |hנֶפֶש|h* ׁ (soul), in phrases like 'abandon my life to |hשַׁחַת|h*'. The whole phrase is a metonomy for death.
\evalev The words for the underworld use the verb |hירד|h*, as opposed to words for a burial place which do not use this verb.
\comp 1. The literal object.   Frame: Hunting2. Metaphorical use of Meaning 1.   Frame: Death
\dfnotes 1. The literal object is a hole in the ground, a pit used as a trap. 2. A metaphorical extention of meaning 1 is the underworld, the dark underground place where the dead are, a trap from which one must escape in order to continue living in the light. Death seems to be a journey that leads to |hשַׁחַת|h*, and this journey can be reversed or interrupted before the final destination is reached. The word |hשַׁחַת|h* by itself or phrases using |hשַׁחַת|h* are a metonymy or euphemism for death. One can be redeemed or ransomed from |hשַׁחַת|h*, or brought up from |hשַׁחַת|h*, kept back from |hשַׁחַת|h*, or not see |hשַׁחַת|h*, thus one does not experience death.
