\intro |hקנא|h* means to become angry in response to a challenge to one's honour.1) A person can cause another to become angry by challenging their honour;2) A person can become angry by something specific that another person does to challenge one's honour;3) A person can become angry when another person represents a challenge to one's honour, even though the other person has not intentionally sought to challenge one's honour;4) A person can become angry in behalf of someone else whose honour has been challenged.
\tnotes Traditional English translations of |hקנא|h* use expressions such as 'to be jealous' or 'to envy'. In some contexts, such as Numbers, chapter 5, these expressions are appropriate. But in many others they are misleading, because evoke the Frames of Hatred, Ownership, or Desire rather than the Frames of Anger and Honour / Shame. More modern English translations use general words, like 'passion' or 'to be passionate'. In so doing they evoke the emotional intensity of |hקנא|h* but they don't help the reader to understand the reason for the intense emotion. The reason for the intense emotion would have been clear to a Hebrew speaker. |hקנא|h* is an understandable, but not always appropriate, response to an honour challenge. The OT understands this response well, but is ambivalent about whether it is always a desirable response.Because |hקנא|h* evokes two Frames and there is no comparable term in English, it may be necessary to use two or more words to carry the same semantic content. The translator would be wise to explore the semantic domain of Honour / Shame as well as Anger within the audience culture. If honour, and avoidance of shame, is a high value, then there may be a cultural equivalent of an agressive response to someone who challenges one's honour. If not, the KTBH translations offered here may provide helpful suggestions.
\hebraist The verb is found in the Piel stem (30x) and in the Hiphil stem (4x). The Hiphil stem expresses a causative relationship (someone causes someone else to become angry). In two occurrences the syntax and context indicates that the Piel stem should be understood as causative (Deu 32:21 and 1Ki 14:22). The meaning of the word shifts according to whether the verb is transitive or intransitive, and whether
\comp All of the meanings and uses described below evoke the same cognitive scenario: a-B challenges the reputation or honour of A b-A is threatened with shame. c-A |bexperiences anger|b*. d-A expresses that anger and attempts to reestablish his or her reputation.|hקנא|h* refers specifically to the experience of anger but brings to mind the whole scenario.There can be variations on the scenario. The challenge to honour may be attributed to the actions of a group or type of people, or it may be a more general state of affairs. The challenge to honour may be intentional or unintentional. In some cases, B does nothing to create a challenge; A simply feels threatened by B's status or reputation. Finally, B may challenge the reputation of C, but it is A that feels the anger on behalf of C. Protecting the reputation of someone else happens due to the close relationships between patrons and clients in Ancient Near Eastern social order.Different aspects of the scenario are brought into focus by how the scenario is expressed grammatically and these affect the nuance of meaning of the expression.Meaning 1: When the verb is transitive and modified by a |hבְּ|h* prepositional phrase, B causes A to experience |hקנא|h* |iwhen|i* B does certain things. (All causative (|ihiphil|i*) forms of the verb are transitive. There are two |ipiel|i* forms that are interpreted as causative because they fit this pattern as well.)Meaning 2: When the verb is intransitive and modified by a |hבְּ|h* prepositional phrase, A experiences |hקנא|h* |iwhen|i* B does certain things or |iwhen|i* certain things are done.Meaning 3: When the verb is transitive and not modified by a prepositional phrase, A experiences |hקנא|h* about B though B has done nothing to provoke a challenge.Meaning 4: When the verb is intransitive and modified by a |hלְ|h* prepositional phrase, A experiences |hקנא|h* on behalf of C (B's role as an Agent is left implicit).Contextual Uses are distinguished either by changes in the participants or by special contextual domains that are brought to mind. So, in Meanings 1 and 4, separate contextual uses are distinguished depending on whether God or humans are Experiencers of |hקנא|h*. Meaning 4 also has distinctions in contextual use depending on whether God or humans are Benefactives. In Meaning 3, different contextual uses are distinguished by whether the Honour challenge is in the context of rivalry for status or in the context of adultery.
\dfnotes |hקנא|h* evokes two Frames: Anger and Honour / Shame. It is used regularly in association with words for anger. The writer of Proverbs classifies it as a form of anger. Anger is an emotional response to a threat to a person's well-being. Various contexts indicate that when |hקנא|h* is used the anger is in response to a threat to a person's honour or status.
\level2 1
\meaning To cause someone to become angry by challenging their honour
\frame Anger; Honour / Shame
\domain Rivalry
\stem Hiphil and causative Piel
\gram The verb is transitive and always modified by a prepositional phrase using |hבְּ|h*. The subject encodes the Agent; the object encodes the Experiencer of the anger; the object of the preposition |hבְּ|h* encodes the Stimulus of the honour challenge.
\eventfr Agent: human or divineExperiencer: divine or humanStimulus: the context which indicates the challenge to honor
\syntagc The Agent that provokes the honour challenge is made explicit as the subject of the causative verb. The Experiencer of the emotion of anger is made explicit as the object. In the other three meanings, the Experiencer of the emotion is brought into focus as the subject of the verb.
\level3 a
\context To cause God to become angry by worshipping rival gods
\domainc Apostasy; Idolatry
\eventfrc Agent: human = people of GodExperiencer: GodStimulus: activity that threatens honour = worshipping rival gods or doing evil
\syntagcc The object of the prepositional phrase which expresses the stimulus is often a metonymy where a thing refers to an event. So 'with strange (gods)' would refer to 'by worshipping and serving foreign gods'; 'with their sins' would refer to 'by the sins that they do'.
\keyref 3!n!Z$!
\keyverse They |bchallenged the honour|b* of their God and provoked him to anger by worshipping idols and serving in their sanctuaries. (KTBH)
\eval RSV provides a traditional translation: 'For they provoked him to anger with their high places; they |bmoved|b* him |bto jealousy|b* with their graven images'. But the English word 'jealousy' does not naturally lead the reader to think of honour and shame. CEV reads: 'God |bdemanded all their love|b*, but they |bmade him angry|b* by worshiping idols. (CEV)' The CEV avoids the word 'jealousy'. Its use of the phrase 'God demanded all their love' may be meaningful for an English audience, but it evokes the domain of marriage which is only a small part of the use of the word, |hקנא|h*. It may actually be misleading for non-Western languages which have a vocabulary for honour and challenges to honour. The KTBH translation makes the frame of Honour / Shame explicit in the translation and allows the anger word in the parallel line to carry the frame of Anger. It also rearranges the parallelism to make the cause and effect order more apparent. The parallelism could be retained by translating: 'They provoked God to anger by serving in sanctuaries of other gods; they |bchallenged his honour|b* by worshipping idols'.
