\keyverse Moses answered, "Why should you be |bso upset|b* about my |bhonour|b*? I wish that the LORD would give his spirit to all his people so that they became prophets!" (KTBH)
\eval |i'Are you jealous on my account?|i*' (NJB) is an unusual use of the word 'jealous'. Jealousy is a selfish emotion in modern English. It would make more sense to use 'zealous' but it is too scholarly for modern English translations. TEV's '|iAre you concerned about my interests?|i*' comes closer to the meaning of the Hebrew word but emasculates the emotional content. The KTBH translation helps to identify Joshua's chief concern, the honour of his patron, and gives a sense of the emotional intensity of the word. Finally, a Why question is much more a rhetorical rebuke in English than is a Yes-No question. Context clearly indicates that Moses intended it as a rebuke.
