\heb קנה
\strong 7069
\level1 1
\pos v
\gloss to buy
\freq 85
\sub מִקְנֶה ,מִקְנָה ,קִנְיָן
\intro 1.  The verb |hקנה|h* ‘to buy’ is used most frequently to refer to a commercial transaction that involves the acquisition of an item or items (including humans) by a particular person for a price. 2.  Buying an item involves a change of ownership and control. 3. These elements of ownership and control allow for several extended meanings of the verb in which items are acquired not through the exchange of money or other items, but through the effort of the person acquiring the item. The effort expended may be that of childbirth (Meaning 2a), God's effort in redeeming people from slavery or in acquiring something by means of warfare (Meaning 2b), and the effort spent on the acquisition of abstract qualities (e.g. wisdom) by a variety of means (Meaning 2c). 4. The verb |hקנה|h* can also mean 'to create' or 'to bring forth' (Meaning 3). This meaning is an extension of Meaning 2a. Rather than referring to physical birth (childbirth) as the means by which one has ownership and control over another, it refers to an item being brought into existence through the effort of the ‘procreator’. As the result of this creative effort, the creator or ‘procreator’ has ownership and control over the item. In the Hebrew Bible, the ‘procreator’ is always God. The item that is created may be the physical world, a human, the people of Israel, or Wisdom.
\altint The interpretation of |hקנה |h*'to buy, acquire' (Meanings 1 and 2) is seldom controversial.  Commentaries, however, reflect alternative interpretations incases where |hקנה |h*means 'to create' or similar (Meaning 3).  In most major English translations, these five occurrences of |hקנה |h*have been consistently translated ‘to create/ to make’ or ‘creator/maker’ when the heavens and earth are the items that are ‘created’ (Gen 14:19, 22). When other types of items are the patients (humans, the people of Israel, or Wisdom), English translations diverge slightly and a wider variety of terminology is used, but most of the terms are still synonyms for creation. An alternate interpretation, however, is often indicated in the notes.  For instance, in Gen 14:19, 22, the NIV lists ‘possessor’ as the alternate translation for ‘creator’ and in Deu 32:6, the alternate translation is ‘who bought you’. In the main text, the NIV uses creation terminology in all of these verses except for Pro 8:22, where procreation terminology is used, i.e. ‘brought me forth’. In Pro 8:22, the NIV note suggests the translation ‘possessed me’.  The alternate interpretations seen in the NIV notes for the meaning of four of these occurrences would be within the range of the examples discussed in Meaning 1. Because God is the agent in all five occurrences, the meaning would probably be an extension of Meaning 1 because it is not likely that God was envisioned as being a participant in a commercial transaction in which a valued item was given to acquire another item. In Deu 32:6 the presence of synonymous verbs that are not economic in nature (|hכון |h*‘to establish’ and |hעשׂה |h*‘to make’) also point to the metaphorical usage of |hקנה|h*. Furthermore, the LXX points to an early interpretation of |hקנה |h*in these occurrences by its use of the translation equivalent |gκτίζω |g*‘to create’ in three of the verses. This evidence that points to the extended usage of |hקנה |h*to refer to creation does not, however, necessitate the assigning of these meanings to a separate root, as is suggested in some lexicons. Rather, the possibility of alternate interpretations points to the related nature of the concepts of acquisition and creation, i.e. created items are the possessions/acquisitions of the one who created them. This is another example that shows that Hebrew words often have a greater range of meaning than their equivalents in English and other languages. The interpretation of קנה in Pro 8:22 has been especially problematic through the centuries. (See Waltke 2004 for a discussion of the various possible interpretations of this verse.) In Pro 8:22, |hקנה |h*‘to buy/create’ refers to the creation of wisdom using an extension of Meaning 2. The extended nature of the meaning of this occurrence is indicated by the use of the term חִיל ‘to bring forth’ in Pro 8:24-25 to describe the same event. The interpretation/translation of Pro 8:22 has varied through the years as a result of the use of this verse in theological debates.  These theological debates may have had some affect on the early revisions of the LXX, which revised the Old Greek from ἔκτισέν ‘he created’ to |gἐκτήσατο|g* ‘he acquired’. As an extension of Meaning 2, this usage of|g |g*|hקנה |h*‘to buy/create’ in Pro 8:22 has been assigned to Meaning 3 ‘to create; to bring forth’. Because of collocational clashes inherent in the image of God giving birth, it is likely that |hקנה |h*will need to be translated as ‘to create’ rather than 'to produce; to bring forth' in many languages.  Similes will also probably need to be used in Pro 8:24-25 to communicate the similar concept of  |hחִיל |h*‘to bring forth’ that is used in Pro 8:24-25. The UBS Handbooks on Genesis, Deuteronomy, and Proverbs discuss the positive and negative factors about choosing to translate this verb as ‘to create’ versus ‘to acquire’ (Reyburn and Fry 1997: 324; Reyburn and Fry 2000; Bratcher and Hatton 2000). Because of the nature of this extended meaning, there is ultimately very little difference in the meaning. As with all extended usages of words, translators are encouraged to carefully check the reader’s understanding of the translation.
\evalev A brief examination of the translation of the phrase |hאָדָ֖ם הִקְנַ֥נִי|h* ‘a man has acquired me’ in Zec 13:5 will quickly illustrate the fact that the MT has been emended and read in a variety of ways in major English translations.  Among the translations examined for KTBH, the most frequent translation was based on the emended text |hאדמה קניני|h* ‘ground is my possession’, as may be seen in the following translations: ‘the land has been my possession’ (RSV, NRS, REB) ‘the land has been my livelihood’ (NIV), ‘the land has been my living’ (NJB), ‘I have farmed the land’ (TEV). In the CEV this phrase is apparently viewed as a parallelism that could be collapsed and hence there is no specific translation of the phrase. The NJPS has a rather unique translation that evidently reads the word |hאדם|h* ‘man’ as being connected with the root meaning ‘red’ and therefore translates it as follows: ‘I was plied with the red stuff’ (NJPS). In addition, the NEB has read the root as being from the verb |hקנא|h* ‘to be jealous’ and has translated it accordingly as ‘who has been schooled in lust’ (Smith 2002: 280). While the majority of the major English translations followed an emended text that leads to a very smooth reading, HOTTP suggests translating it as ‘a man has acquired me <as a slave>’, which follows the MT (Barthélemy, Prophetical Books II 1980: 422). The LXX translates the verb by the term |gἄνθρωπος ἐγέννησέν με|g* ‘a man has given birth to me’, which seems to indicate that the translator was reading a text similar to the MT, though he did not use the unmarked translation equivalent |gκτάομαι |g*‘to acquire’ for the translation of the verb |hקנה|h* ‘to buy’. Some translations, such as the Tok Pisin Bible, reflect an interpretation based on the MT. This translation reads as follows: Mi stap wokboi nating bilong wanpela man ‘I am the slave of one man.’ The Tok Pisin translation reinforces the preceding statement, i.e. he is just a slave and therefore he could not be a prophet.
\comp The meanings of |hקנה|h* ‘to buy’ can be divided into three groups:  1. those that refer to a literal commercial transaction (Meaning 1a-c)2. those in which 'buy' is used with an extended meaning to refer to a type of acquisition (Meanings 2a-c) 3. those that refer to the event of creation (Meaning 3), an extension of Meaning 2a. Meaning 1. The basic event (focus: the commercial transaction); perspective: buyerMeaning 1a. Patient: thingMeaning 1b. Patient: humanMeaning 1c. Patient: brideMeaning 2. Extension of Meaning 1 (focus: control and ownership) Meaning 2a: To acquire a human being through the process of childbirth Meaning 2b: To acquire authority over a people group or a piece of land by means of a demonstration of power Meaning 2c: To acquire a moral valueMeaning 3. Extension of Meaning 2a that refers to the event of creation
