\heb חֻקָּה
\strong 2708
\pos ncf
\gloss law
\freq 104
\intro The general sense for HUQQAH is : A customary activity that is established or required by an authority. It is applied to the following contexts:1. God establishing the customary activity of natural celestial cycles which provide night and day, and seasons.2. God requiring the people of Israel to do specific customary activities, especially religious rituals3. Nations and kings establishing customary activities which are to be practiced by their people. This can include both good and bad practices, such as idolatry.
\comp The most frequent use of XUQQAH  is in Leviticus 26 x; the second most frequent is in Ezekiel 21x. Between the two they comprise almost half of the instances of XUQQAH in the Hebrew Bible.
\dfnotes Comparison with XOQ:There are some interesting distributions between XOQ and XUQQAH.The most frequent use of XUQQAH  is in Leviticus 26 x; the second most frequent is in Ezekiel 21x. Between the two they comprise almost half of the instances of XUQQAH in the Hebrew Bible.On the other hand, XOQ is most frequent in Psalms, in particular Psalms 119, and in Deuteronomy.31x in the Psalms of which 22 in Psalm 119; 21x in DeuteronomyThe distribution of morphological and grammatical element in relation with the two forms is also quite interesting:XUQQAH is most frequently found in the following constructions:   - Plural form with possessive pronominal suffixes 1st pers. sing, 3rd pers. singular, and less frequently in a noun construct - the HUQQOT of X (of a person)   - Singular - in a construct construction with the word specifying the type of XUQQAH, or identifying the person giving the HUQQAH. It very rarely occurs in singular non-suffixed form, or with other types of suffixes.XOQ on the other hand, has the following grammatical distribution:   - Plural form as an independent non-suffixed form, or with a second person singular suffix, but rarely with 3rd person sing. or 1st person sing. suffix.    - Singular form allows any type of possessive pronoun suffix, but is rarely in construct form (except with 'olam)The semantic distinction is a little less pronounced than the grammatical distribution (see XOQ entry to fill in) While XUQQAH often refers to specific laws concerning the ritual and cultic activities (sacrifices, festivals especially the passover, etc.), it can also be used in the context of both moral and cultic laws (see Leviticus 18). XOQ, on the other hand is less frequently associated with any particular law. It appears that while there is some semantic distinction between the two, there seems to be rather a choice between the two terms based on preference of morphological form and composition, perhaps for reasons of metre, and sound patterns. When examining Psalm 119, which uses almost exclusively XOQ in its plural form with the second person singular possessive pronoun suffix, it has one single instance of the use of XUQQAH in plural, with the second person singular suffix. (Psalm 119:16). There is no known reason for this, but it seems clear that it is meant to mean the same as XOQ.  There is no clear sound pattern, or semantic reason that would favor the feminine form. Perhaps there was a need for and additional syllable, to maintain the metre and rhythm of the line?In Leviticus, there is a clear distribution pattern. There are only two instances  where XOQ means |ilaw|i* : in Lev 10:11as a generic term for laws and in Lev 26:46, the very last verse of the book, which gives a concluding summary with a list of all the legal words to refer to all of the laws in Leviticus. Curiously the feminine form is not found here, though it is the term used for law throughout the book, including three verses previous in 26:43(with 1st person singular suffix). Might this concluding line be inserted at a later date?Otherwise, all other references of XOQ in Leviticus have the meaning of |ia prescribed portion|i*, and is found primarily in the singular form. On the other hand, In Deuteronomy, XOQ is not used to refer to this meaning.Deuteronomy, on the other hand, seems to governed by a morphological distribution scheme. Both the feminine and masculine forms are used to mean |ilaw|i*. XOQ is used in the plural form with no pronominal suffix except in 4 instances (out of 21), where it has the third person sing. suffix.  XUQQAH has only 8 references in Deuteronomy, and every single one of them are in the plural with a third person singular suffix. Both forms are found in the same syntactic and  semantic contexts - meaning |ilaw|i*, and used as part of a list of legal terms. Never are both terms used together in a list, as is if to indicate different types of laws.Comparing the use in the context of human laws. For XOQ, it is used generally in the singular form to mean a decree that is instituted by an authority as a law, or an established practice. One can have an unjust law (Isa 10:1). In the expression - X instituted as a XOQ.  XUQQAH in the context of humans as agents is always in plural form, with no specific individual agent, rather generally 'nations', and almost always with negative meaning : Do not follow the XUQQOT of the other nations.The suggestion that XOQ and XUQQAH differenciate meaningwise in that XOQ is |ilaw|i* and that XUQQAH is |ian established practice|i* is not always clear that it is so. For example in --- where the custom of mourning the daughter of Jepthah became a XOQ,  versus - do not follow the HUQQOT of the nations. Both can be translated as a |ipractice|i* or a |icustom.|i* See Eze 20:18 NJPS - I warned their children in the wilderness: Do not follow the practices (XUQQIM) of your fathers, do not keep their ways, and do not defile yourselves with their fetishes. And then Eze 20:19  NJPS - I the Lord am your God: Follow My laws (XUQQOT) and be careful to observe My rules.In some cases, one can perceive that HOQ can mean - an imposed decree that must be followed, while XUQQAH could mean - an established practice. (But see also MISHPAT, which can also mean custom is certain contexts.Both terms are frequently found in the collocation  with MISHPAT, and seem to have the same meaning. The distribution of use of the feminine form versus masculine form seems to be based on morphological and sound pattern combinations. Singular and Pl without pronoun suffixes - both are always in the masculine form : XOQIM and MISHPATIM. Pl with first person suffixes - XUQQOTAI ve MISHPATAI, is the general rule, though there are a few exceptions.
\addinfo Discussion of the frequent collocation - XOQ(QAH) ve MISHPAT, sometimes singular, sometimes plural, sometimes in parallel constructions.
