\intro 1. The verb |hצוה|h* is used to express any directive given by anyone in a superior, authority position to anyone under his authority as a means of imposing one's will on the other person and requiring them to do something. This meaning has various translations in English: |icommand, decree, instruct, give orders, tell someone to do something, charge.|i* It is used both in the context of rules and regulations, and laws, as well as in the context of orders for a specific one-time activity. It should never be understood as simply advice, counsel, or exhortation. Although the recipient may have the free will to reject the command, it is to the peril of his well-being, and in some cases, to his life.There are also different authority relationships for which the |hצוה|h* may be used: divine-human, kings-subjects, parent-child, master-servant, etc.  When more than one type of relationship is involved between two people, the authority role may change depending on the context. For example, in Esther, Mordecai, as uncle, |icommands|i* Esther not to reveal her origins to anyone (Est 2:20). Later, it is Esther, as queen who |iorders|i* Mordecai to observe a fast (Est 4:17). So though she does not have authority over Mordecai as niece, she does have authority over him as queen, and thus can command him.2. One extension of this basic meaning is: |ito give authority and command|i* another person to do a specific task. One specific example of this is when Moses |icommissioned |i*Joshua to take his position as leader of the Israelites as they enter Canaan. This sense is also used in the context of |igiving final instructions |i*to one's household before dying, as well as |itransmitting a message and/or commands through an intermediary|i*. 3. A second extension of the meaning is used to express God's acts of power and creation. The verb means: |ito decree an event and to make that event happen, i.e. to cause something to happen|i*. Examples of this use can be found in God |icausing |i*acts in all of his creation, the skies, the earth, the animals, and even causing people to act a certain way, especially causing enemies to destroy the Israelites. He can also |icommand|i* blessings, loyalty, His covenant, salvation, and victory.
\tnotes Depending on the language, the translation of the word |hצוה |h*may vary widely according to the context. In each case, it is important to take into consideration who is commanding whom; whether the command involves a one-time order, a binding regulation, or the investment of authority on another person; whether the recipient of the command is a willful human being or is simply an instrument in the hands of God who has no choice but to do what God says. Where the command is negative, terms such as f|iorbid,|i* may be more appropriate. See below for suggestions and examples.The words |ipermit |i*and |ipromise|i* are used by certain translations in a few limited contexts. In these cases, it seems that the context guides the interpretation more than does the basic sense of the word. The word |hצוה|h* always refers to the communication of a requirement by an authority or of the causation of an action by an authority.
\comp All five meanings of |hצוה|h* include the following five basic components: 1. An individual with authority and power over persons and objects under that authority (e.g. God, angel, kings, elder family members, any human authory figure)2. The authority wills a specific action or event be accomplished by specified agents under his authority3. The authority communicates his will to the designated agent of the action. 4. The will of the recipient of the communication is not taken into account 5. The authority powerfully imposes his will on the recipientThere is a parameter that distinguishes the first three meanings from the last two. In the first three, the agent of the action does have the choice to accept or refuse to comply to the will of the authority, but the refusal to do so will bring about serious consequences. In Meaning 5, the recipient of the command actually has no choice but to comply to the will of the authority. This sense of total obligation translates into the sense of causation, and in this context |hצוה|h* becomes a speech act; the command produces a powerful effect.  The notion of verbal communication of the command becomes figurative.  God is the only agent of these kinds of powerful speech acts. The agents of these caused actions are any and all aspects of creation both animate and inanimate (e.g. universe, rain, animals, people, abstract qualities).Meaning 4, the sense of conferring authority to another person, is somewhere in between. The person concerned may have a choice to refuse to act, but the conferring of authority is not a matter of choice on the part of the recipient. He automatically has the responsibility. It simply seems to be assumed that he will do the job.The distinctions between the first three meanings are minimal. The first provides a generic sense of the verb, while the second groups together all instances of the verb that refer to regulations and legislation. The third meaning comprises those contexts in which the word refers to one time orders. However, there are cases, where the the distinction between meanings 2 and 3 are not clear. 
