\sub מֹועֵצָה ,עֵצָה
\intro 1. The meanings of this word are all related to a central meaning, ‘to advise, to counsel’2. The relative social status of the people giving and receiving advice helps distinguish the meanings3. Most commonly it is used where wise people advise other people who are higher in status (Meaning 1a).4. Sometimes it is used when someone higher in status confers with others greater in wisdom (Meaning 1b).5. Sometimes it is used where social equals confer together (Meaning 3).6. Sometimes it is used where there is only one person involved, human or divine, who plans what he wants to do in the future, perhaps being thought to take counsel with himself (Meaning 4).7. There is one special use (Meaning 2) where the word appears to refer to giving a prophetic oracle.
\hebraist Closely related to |hיעץ|h* is the verb |hעוץ|h*, which occurs only twice (Jdg 19:30; Isa 8:10) but has the same meaning.
\comp 1. Frame: Counsel; Agent: superior in wisdom; Patient: superior in status	1a. Stem: Qal, Niphal; Focus: one giving advice	1b. Stem: Niphal; Focus: one receiving advice2. Frame: Divination; Agent: prophet3. Frame: Deliberation; Agents: equal in status; Patient: none4. Frame: Planning; Agent: individual; Patient: none	4a. Agent: human	4b. Agent: God
\dfnotes יעץ 'to advise, counsel, plan' and עֵצָה 'counsel, plan' have Wisdom as an Intrinsic Domain. Typically, a person senses a lack of wisdom and asks a wiser man to give advice. As is the case with other wisdom terms, the advice given or the plan formed can be for good and for evil.Under Meaning 1 we have subsumed instances of the Niphal, in the Contextual use 'to confer together with wise men in order to obtain advice'. In most dictionaries, the Niphal signals a different meaning, but in KTBH we look at the Event. The Event is that a wise man gives advice to someone who is less wise. In the cases under Meaning 1b, we see the same: X, the superior in status, but not in wisdom, allows himself to be advised by Y, the superior in wisdom, but not in status.Normally, advice is given (יעץ) by a person lower in status to a higher person, whereby the higher person, e.g. a king, can follow the advice or reject it. An exalted person does not normally give advice to his subordinates, but |icommands|i* them (צוה). When this pattern is flouted, this can be significant. Normally God has the authority to command, but in Psa 16:7, He condescends to give advice.What makes Meaning 3 ('to deliberate') different is that the participants of this event are equal. Together they are Agents, and there is no Patient.Meaning 4 seems to be related to Meaning 1 in this way, that the verb that denoted (internal) deliberation came to be used for the outcome, 'to plan' / 'to decide'. The event is different, however, because there is only one participant, the Agent.
\level2 1
\meaning To suggest to someone how to respond to a problem or, more generally, what he might do in the future
\frame Counsel
\domain Wisdom
\stem Qal, Niphal, Hithpael
\gram The participant roles do not correspond neatly to the grammatical roles. The grammatical subject always indicates the Agent, but the object can denote either Patient or Content. In other words: the object can denote (a) the advice, but also (b) the person to whom advice is given; (c) both can be combined. Examples:(a) In Exo 18:19 Jethro says to Moses |hאִיעָצְךָ|h* 'I will counsel you'. Moses is the Patient.(b) In 2Sa 16:23 we read about the advice (|hעֵצָה|h*) that Ahithophel used to give (|hיעץ|h*). The advice is the Content.(c) In 1Ki 1:12 the prophet Nathan says to Bathsheba: 'Let me counsel you a counsel'. Bathsheba is the Patient, the counsel is the Content.In some cases there is a third party who will be the victim of the advice (in KTBH terms he is still called 'Benefactive'). This Benefactive is indicated by a preposition (|hעַל|h* 'against'). E.g. 2Sa 17:21 'Ahithophel has adviced such and such against you'.
