\sub בַּיִן, בִּינָה, בֵּנַיִם, תְּבוּנָה
\intro The verb |hבין|h* is used to denote various degrees of mental activity with respect to something, from 'noticing' and 'observing carefully' to 'understanding'. Since in the Hebrew worldview personal characteristics are never sharply separated from the actions that result from them, the same verb can also mean 'to be understanding, prudent' and 'to act with understanding'.
\hebraist According to the grammars of Gesenius-Kautzsch-Cowley (73a) and Joüon-Muraoka (54f; 81d), the usual and old form is |hהבין|h* ; hence the imperfect |hיבין|h* is a Hiphil. The forms that morphologically can only be Qal forms are probably secondary hypercorrections, since its Hiphil had acquired a causative meaning, which it originally did not have.
\altint Some recent dictionaries, e.g. NIDOTTE, present |hבין|h* as quite a straightforward entry. Although the rendering of this verb is not so complicated as that of other verbs, it has more contextual uses than is sometimes realized.
\evalev Evidence from Ben Sira and Qumran literature has not been covered.
