\dfnotes In his Exodus commentary, Cassuto aptly paraphrases the three terms as follows (31:3):|i"with wisdom |i*[|hחָכְמָה|h*] that is, expert knowledge of the techniques of workmanship and the ability to employ them;|iwith understanding  |i*[|hתְּבוּנָה|h*] - that is, the capacity to deduce one thing from another and to find a way of solving every problem that might arise in the course of the work;|iwith knowledge|b |b*[|hדַּעַת|h*] - that is, the store of expertness that continues to grow relative to a basic skill as a result of practical experience." (pp. 401-402, like|iwise J.I. Durham, Exodus (WBC) ad loc.). From these definitions we should rather translate the terms as, respectively: knowledge, insight/understanding, expertise. It makes sense to translate |hדַּעַת|h* as expertise, because the verb ידע means 'to be familiar with’.|i*
