\heb ישׁר
\strong 03474
\pos v
\gloss To be upright, make level
\freq 27
\sub יָשָׁר, יֹשֶׁר, יִשְׁרָה, מִישׁוֹר, מֵישָׁרִים
\intro ·	The term has one literal sense and three extensions ·	The literal spatial sense is ‘straight, level’·	Corresponding to this literal sense, there is a causative, where someone makes something straight or level·	One sense extends ‘straight, level’ to ‘without obstacles’ and implies successfulness.·	Another sense extends ‘straight, level’ to the area of moral conduct and implies uprightness of life and speech·	This sense can be applied to God or to people·	A final sense extends the moral sense to situations where someone evaluates another’s actions, but the moral aspect is absent
\comp 1 Frame: Spatial;				Stem:  Qal2 Frame: Spatial;				Stem:  Piel, Pual, Hiphil	2a  Specific frame: One dimensional objects or motion	2b  Specific frame: Two dimensional surfaces3 Frame: Successfulness4 Frame: Morality: Morally good;	Stem:  Qal	4a Patient: human; Agent (Evaluator): God;	Domains: Divine evaluation	4b Patient: human;				Domains: Cultic arrangements; Human conduct5 Frame: Morality: Morally good;	Stem:  Piel6 Frame: Evaluation; Personal choice
\addinfo 1. The root |hישׁר|h* has one literal sense and two metaphorical extensions, though they are not all attested for every term related to the root. The literal sense is less common than the extensions, but it is sufficiently well-attested to establish it as the basis for the extensions. All three senses are have parallels in other languages of the ANE.The literal sense refers to something that is straight, if it is one-dimensional, or level, if it is two-dimensional. English lexicalises this distinction between straight and level, but Hebrew does not.The first metaphorical extension maps the Physical shape Frame on to the Successfulness Frame. If a journey is literally |hישׁר|h*, then it is free from detours and diversions. Similarly, if it is metaphorically |hישׁר|h*, then it is free from detours, dangers and other problems. If land is literally |hישׁר|h*, then it is free from hills, bumps and other obstacles. Similarly, if it is metaphorically |hישׁר|h*, then it is free from difficulties and from obstacles that might cause stumbling. In either case, the metaphor implies that the venture in view will be successful and safe.The second metaphorical extension maps the Physical shape Frame on to the Moral uprightness Frame. This is similar to the English metaphor ‘uprightness’ in that it is Physical shape that is the metaphorical source. However, in English, it is specifically verticality that is the source whereas in Hebrew it is straight/level. The mapping seems to be that, as a journey or land that is |hישׁר |h*is free from physical or topographical irregularities, so a life that is |hישׁר |h*is free from moral irregularities.The two metaphors are linked not only in the derivation but also that, especially in Proverbs, the morally upright life will be a successful life.Another sense of |hישׁר |h*appears to be a further extension of the second metaphor in which the moral nuance is absent and all that is left is the personal preference of the one who evaluates the person or conduct.The verb has, in addition, various causative and declarative senses, all of which are closely related to the senses described above.2. |hלֵב|h* or |hלֵבָב|h* collocate with the root |hישׁר|h* as attribute, in a construct pair, subject-predicate or other way, 13 times and with the root |hתמם|h* 6 times. By contrast, the |hצדק|h* root is never used as an attribute of |hלֵב|h* or |hלֵבָב|h*. This suggests that |hישׁר|h* or |hתמם|h* may be used of an inward disposition, whereas |hצדק|h* is not. The latter refers primarily to outward behaviour and collocates with verbs or verbal nouns of doing 35 times. That is not to say that |hישׁר|h* and |hתמם|h* are never used of outward behaviour, since both are used as attributes of |hדֶּרֶךְ|h*,16 and 11 times respectively. (Data from Even Shoshan).
