\freq 64
\sub תָּם, תֹּם, תֻּמָּה, תָּמִים, תֻּמִּים, מְתֹם
\intro ·	The term has one main literal sense and one extension·	The extended sense is rare for the verb but much more common for related terms which are rarely used in the literal sense·	The literal sense conveys ‘completeness’, in that some event, attribute or thing is complete or finished·	Corresponding to this literal sense, there is a causative, where someone causes something to be complete or to cease·	The other sense extends ‘completeness’ to ‘morally blameless’·	This sense is applied both to people and to God
\comp 1 Frame:  Completeness;		Stem: Qal	1a Domains:  Death	1b Domains:  Time	1c Domains:  Miscellaneous;	Participant Roles:  Patient	1d Domains:  Miscellaneous;	Participant Roles:  Agent, Event2 Frame:  Completeness;		Stem: Hiphil (Qal?)3 Frame:  Morality: Morally good;	Stem: Qal, Hithpael, Hiphil	3a Patient:  God	3b Patient:  human
\addinfo Three distinct Meanings have been identified for the root |hתמם|h*:	1 to be complete, finished, lacking nothing	2 to be morally blameless	3 to be without defectThe first is the most literal Meaning and the second is derived from it by extension to the Morality Frame, in the sense of moral completeness. The English term ‘wholehearted’ conveys the sense of completeness, but lacks the moral direction implicit in |hתמם|h*, since it is possible to be wholehearted in pursuit of evil. English translations have traditionally render the root by terms related to ‘blameless’ when they need an adjective or ‘integrity’ when they need a noun.The third Meaning is a technical term only used to describe animals acceptable for sacrifice and only attested for the adjective |hתָּמִים|h*. It may derive by extension directly from the sense 'complete', or it may derive from the Meaning ‘blameless’, either transferred from people who offer the sacrificial animals to the animals or from God to animals that are acceptable to him.|hלֵב|h* or |hלֵבָב|h* collocate with the root |hישׁר|h* as attribute, in a construct pair, subject-predicate or other way, 13 times and with the root |hתמם|h* 6 times. By contrast, the |hצדק|h* root is never used as an attribute of |hלֵב|h* or |hלֵבָב|h*. This suggests that |hישׁר|h* or |hתמם|h* may be used of an inward disposition, whereas |hצדק|h* is not. The latter refers primarily to outward behaviour and collocates with verbs or verbal nouns of doing 35 times. That is not to say that |hישׁר|h* and |hתמם|h* are never used of outward behaviour, since both are also used as attributes of |hדֶּרֶךְ|h*, 16 and 11 times respectively. (Data from Even Shoshan).
