\heb צדק
\strong 06663
\pos v
\gloss to be righteous, to declare to be righteous, to act justly
\freq 41
\sub צַדִּיק, צֶדֶק, צְדָקָה
\intro ·	The term always includes the idea of conformity to a norm·	In various contexts, that norm is the covenant, wisdom principles or societal norms·	Most often, it describes general human behaviour according to a norm·	A person’s status in the eyes of a community may be distinguished from that person’s behaviour, but they are never separated. People have righteous status because their behaviour is righteous·	It is used of human rulers and judges when they fulfil their duty according to the appropriate norm·	It is used of God when he acts in accordance with the covenant, either in giving well-being to faithful Israel or punishing unfaithful Israel·	It is used in various senses which may be grouped as ‘causative’, but with varying nuances·	Sometimes the causative nuance is a declaration that someone’s behaviour is righteous thereby conferring righteous status on that person·	Sometimes the causative nuance is showing by contrast that the behaviour of someone else is relatively righteous·	Sometimes the causative nuance is bringing about a change so that someone or something is in accordance with a norm·	It has also a number of less-used Meanings, but they all share the idea of conformity to a norm
\altint Scholarly debate about the |hצדק |h*word group has centred around two issues relevant to KTBH.1. There have been two main approaches to the basic meaning of the word group. Some see a reference to ‘accordance with a norm’ while others understand it to refer to ‘fidelity to a relationship’ (Seifrid 2001, 416). Many instances of the terms could be subsumed under the latter understanding, especially those where God rescues Israel from their enemies. However, contra von Rad (OTT 1.377), there is a significant number of instances where God is said to be |hצַדִּיק |h*when he acts with punitive justice against unfaithful Israel (eg Dan 9:7, 14, 16; Neh 9:33; 2Ch 12:1-6), which do not fit well with ‘fidelity to a relationship’. It thus seems better to take the |hצדק |h*word group to refer to ‘in accordance with a norm’. The most concrete use of the terms, where weights and measures are to have the attribute |hצֶדֶק |h*(Lev 19:36; Deu 25:15; Ezk 45:10), fits well into this understanding. 2. This raises the second issue in scholarly debate, because the relevant norm is very rarely explicit in the immediate context, and it has to be recovered from a wider context. Some take the Covenant as the norm against which righteousness is evaluated (eg TDOT, TWOT). This provides a framework which accommodates most instances of the |hצדק |h*word group, though not all. Nonetheless it provides a helpful starting point.·	When Israel is faithful, they are acting in accord with the covenant stipulations and they are righteous.·	When God blesses faithful Israel, he is acting in accord with the covenant blessings and he is righteous.·	When God punishes unfaithful Israel, he is acting in accord with the covenant curses and he is still righteous.·	Even when God restores repentant Israel, he is acting in accord with the covenant and he is righteous.In fact, if covenant is the norm by which behaviour is assessed, the relational and norm-based understandings are very close, in that a covenant is essentially relational, but includes terms to which both parties are expected to adhere.	Seifrid, however, notes that the |hצדק |h*root rarely collocates with |hבְּרִית |h*and expresses surprise at this, since ‘both |hבְּרִית |h*and the |hצדק |h*word group have fields of meaning having to do with relationships, and both have ethical and juridical dimensions’. He concludes that covenant is not the relevant norm for most instances of the |hצדק |h*word group, but rather the context is creation and |hצדק |h*should be seen as ‘order’ (2001, 423).	Against Seifrid, however, other terms which do have strong covenantal overtones such as the אמן root and more significantly |hתֹּורָה |h*and  |hחֶסֶד|h*, and also the formula |hוְהָיוּ־לִי לְעָם וַאֲנִי אֶהְיֶה לָהֶם לֵאלֹהִים|h* ‘they will be my people and I will be their God’ in Zec 8:8 do collocate with the |hצדק |h*root. Furthermore, where the |hצדק |h*root and |hבְּרִית |h*do collocate, the logical link between them is strong. For example, Neh 9:8, ... |hוְכָרֹות עִמֹּו הַבְּרִית לָתֵת אֶת־אֶרֶץ הַכְּנַעֲנִי ... לָתֵת לְזַרְעֹו וַתָּקֶם אֶת־דְּבָרֶיךָ כִּי צַדִּיק אָתָּה׃|h* ‘…you made the covenant with him to give him the land of the Canaanites …, to give it to his descendants, and you fulfilled your words for you are righteous’. Similarly, in Dan 9:4 God keeps the covenant, but in vv 5-6 Israel does not. Then, in v 7, God is righteous, but Israel is in trouble. The analysis in KTBH thus takes Covenant as the relevant norm, and thus a contextual Domain for both divine and human behaviour wherever it seems appropriate.	As noted above, for the small number of instances of the root in Genesis, the norm can be seen more generally as societal norms. After Sinai, the terms of the covenant were expected to replace or supplement those societal norms. The other group of instances not linked to the covenant domain is where the root occurs in the Wisdom literature where the covenant is generally considered not to be a prominent feature.	This departs from Seifrid’s understanding less than might be thought. He takes the wider view of righteousness as a creational concept, but recognises that many instances of the |hצדק |h*word group occur in covenant contexts, whereas KTBH sees the covenant context as more fundamental to the Hebrew world-view but recognises that occasionally the Biblical writers use the terms in a wider context.
\qumran TLOT notes that 'the OT correlation-God conveys |hצֶדֶק|h* only on the one who is |hצַדִּיק|h*-has dissolved. The divine |hצְדָקָה|h* is associated with the forgiveness of sins: "Through his |hצְדָקֹות|h* my sins are wiped out" (1QS 11:3, 12-14; cf. 10:11). Such statements stand on the threshold between the OT and the NT and are already reminiscent of the Pauline discussion of the |gδικαιοσύνη Θεοῦ|g*.'
\nt A separation between righteous behaviour and status before God as a righteous person (contrast Frame and Domain Notes) surfaces in Romans, most explicitly in 4:4 '... God who justifies the wicked' (NIV). In the flow of Paul's logic, since 'there is no-one righteous, not even one' (3:10), no-one could have righteous status before God in any other way.
\comp 1 Frame: Righteousness;	Non-causative	1a Focus: Behaviour;	Domains: Covenant	1b Focus: Behaviour;	Domains: Societal norms	1c Focus: Behaviour;	Domains: Wisdom	1d Focus: Status;	Domains: Covenant; Wisdom2 Frame: Righteousness;	Causative nuance:  Declarative	2a Focus: Behaviour	2b Focus: Status3 Frame: Righteousness;	Causative nuance: Demonstrative4 Frame: Righteousness; 	Causative nuance: Causative5 Frame: Order6 Frame: Rightness; Justice	6a Agent:  God;			Domains: Covenant; Un/faithfulness	6b Patient:  God's legislation	Domains: Covenant; Legislation7 Frame: Truth
\dfnotes Two elements seem to be in the righteousness frame that is activated by most uses of the root: righteous behaviour and status as a righteous person in the eyes of a community. Sometimes the status aspect of the frame is clearly in focus and these instances of the terms are distinguished. More often, however, either behaviour is in focus, or there is no clear focus, and these are grouped together.In Protestant theology, and arguably in the NT, a distinction is made between righteous status and righteous behaviour. This distinction is found even in discussion of the OT, but it is probably too modern and too western and owes more to the Reformation debates than to the Hebrew usage (cf Seifrid 2001, 422). One whose behaviour is righteous should be accorded righteous status eg |hוְהִצְדִּיקוּ אֶת־הַצַּדִּיק וְהִרְשִׁיעוּ אֶת־הָרָשָׁע|h* ‘they will declare righteous the righteous and they will declare wicked the wicked’ (Deu 25:1). Any reversal of that is prohibited eg |hמַצְדִּיק רָשָׁע וּמַרְשִׁיעַ צַדִּיק תֹּועֲבַת יְהוָה גַּם־שְׁנֵיהֶם |h*‘one who declares righteous the wicked and one who declares wicked the righteous are both an abomination to Yahweh’ (Pro 17:15). In cognitive terms, declaring the righteous wicked, or the converse, is an example of frame-breaking, because it runs counter to the expectations raised by the frame that is evoked. The concepts ‘behaviour’ and ‘status’ are distinguishable in the Hebrew mind-set, but not separable. Thus KTBH distinguishes between righteous status and righteous behaviour only to the extent that one or other is in focus in a particular context.	There are rare exceptions where people have a righteous status before God in spite of their unrighteous behaviour eg Isa 53:11, where the |hצדק|h* root is explicit, and also Psalm 51, where the root it is not used but the same idea is present.|hלֵב|h* or |hלֵבָב |h*collocate with the root |hישׁר |h*as attribute, in a construct pair, subject-predicate or other way, 13 times and with the root |hתמם|h* 6 times. By contrast, the |hצדק |h*root is never used as an attribute of |hלֵב |h*or |hלֵבָב|h*. This suggests that |hישׁר |h*or |hתמם |h*may be used of an inward disposition, whereas |hצדק |h*is not. The latter refers primarily to outward behaviour and collocates with verbs or verbal nouns of doing 35 times. That is not to say that |hישׁר |h*and |hתמם |h*are never used of outward behaviour, since both are used as attributes of |hדֶּרֶךְ|h* (16 and 11 times respectively; data from Even Shoshan).
