\colc אֱמֶת
\pgloss truth
\refsc 7!K!)."
\not (a) The |hמִן|h* that follows is comparative, so the righteousness of Israel is only relative to the greater unrighteousness of Judah.
\notfr (a) NOTE
\notsp (a) NOTE
\notpt (a) NOTE
\notxx (a) NOTE
\not (b) It is possible that Absalom intended to gain support by giving judgement to potential supporters without regard to the justness of their case. TOTC hints at this, but not other commentaries, and the translations do not reflect this possibility.
\notfr (b) NOTE
\notsp (b) NOTE
\notpt (b) NOTE
\notxx (b) NOTE
\not (c) The reflexive nuance is indicated by |hנֶפֶשׁ|h* with a reflexive suffix as direct object.
\notfr (c) NOTE
\notsp (c) NOTE
\notpt (c) NOTE
\notxx (c) NOTE
\not (d) The focus and the precise nuance of the Hiphil to be understood here is closely linked to the identity of the Isaiah's servant figure. A human Servant at about the time of the exile could do no more than vindicate or save 'the many'. This thinking may lie behind the view of TDOT that this means 'deliver, help' as in Psa 82:3 and Isa 50:8 (cf BDB 'justify, vindicate the cause of, save' and HALOT 'to assist someone towards his rights'). However, the difficulty of identifying a suitable human referent suggests to others that Isaiah's Servant figure is Messianic prophecy in the traditional sense. In that case, he is able to declare righteous the many whose own behaviour was not righteous.
\notfr (d) NOTE
\notsp (d) NOTE
\notpt (d) NOTE
\notxx (d) NOTE
\not (e) Samaria and Sodom only appeared righteous because Judah's unrighteousness was even greater.
\notfr (e) NOTE
\notsp (e) NOTE
\notpt (e) NOTE
\notxx (e) NOTE
\not (f) In modern versions the causation implied by the Hiphil from is expressed in various ways, but the parallel with |hמַשְׂכִּלִים|h* suggests teaching or persuasion to act in covenant faithfulness.
\notfr (f) NOTE
\notsp (f) NOTE
\notpt (f) NOTE
\notxx (f) NOTE
\not (g) It is possible that Elihu is denying Job's claim to righteous behaviour (v 9), but the way argument proceeds seems to be to correct Job's view of God. Thus in v 12, Elihu is saying, 'In this [your understanding of God] you are not correct' (cf NICOT and KD, but against this see NIDOTTE).
\notfr (g) NOTE
\notsp (g) NOTE
\notpt (g) NOTE
\notxx (g) NOTE
\not (h) This assignment assumes ellipsis of a speech verb, 'let them bring in their witnesses [so that they may testify] they were right'. Otherwise the Qal would have to mean 'so that they may be justified, proved right' which would be a passive of a declarative and thus surprising for a Qal. Some translations may hint at the former understanding: eg 'to prove they were right' (NIV) or 'to testify they were right' (NET).
\notfr (h) NOTE
\notsp (h) NOTE
\notpt (h) NOTE
\notxx (h) NOTE
