\notfr (a) NOTE
\notsp (a) NOTE
\notpt (a) NOTE
\notxx (a) NOTE
\not (b) NJPS, '... Or captives retrieved from a victor?' attempts to follow MT, which is supported by the Targum and probably LXX, and make sense of |hצַדִּיק|h* in this context, but 'victor' would be a unique Use of |hצַדִּיק |h*and stretches its meaning too far. 1QIs|ua|u*, supported by Syr and Vul, reads |hעָרִיץ |h*'fierce warrior', as in v 25, and most translations other than NJPS have followed this reading. NICOT notes the tendency of 1QIs|ua|u* to smooth out difficult readings, but accepts the emendation, as does HOTTP, with degree of probability C. If MT is retained, perhaps the translation of KD might be the best '... or will the captive host of the righteous escape?', though, as noted by Young, this destroys the parallelism.
\notfr (b) NOTE
\notsp (b) NOTE
\notpt (b) NOTE
\notxx (b) NOTE
\not (c) This is difficult in that both the identity of the singers and the identity of 'the righteous' are uncertain. The majority view seems to be that the righteous one is Yahweh, as the context seems to require, since in the two previous verses it is Yahweh whose praise has been sung in vv 14-15. NICOT notes the points made to the contrary by KD, but regards the context as conclusive. As for the singers, WBC notes 'Who are these who shout encouragement to Yahweh from the outer edges of the land which forms this stage of action? Are they the Israelites who have been exiled to far places? Are they members of Yahweh’s heavenly court? Are they admirers from among the nations? They remain unidentified. It is sufficient to note that Yahweh’s work is known and appreciated.'
\notfr (c) NOTE
\notsp (c) NOTE
\notpt (c) NOTE
\notxx (c) NOTE
\not (d) KTBH follows most modern translations (except RSV) in assuming a reference to God as the righteous one. 'Although |hצַדִּיק|h* elsewhere in this book always refers to a human being, here it refers to God because it is in apposition to "the one who casts down the wicked," who can only be the LORD' (NICOT). For further arguments supporting this assignment, see KD.
\notfr (d) NOTE
\notsp (d) NOTE
\notpt (d) NOTE
\notxx (d) NOTE
\not (e) Verse 21 sets the legal context, so this is a matter of getting a favourable verdict.
\notfr (e) NOTE
\notsp (e) NOTE
\notpt (e) NOTE
\notxx (e) NOTE
\not (f) In the mouth of Pharaoh, this is not a confession of faith, but an acknowledgement that in the current confrontation it is Yahweh who is in the right and Pharaoh and his people who are in the wrong. Note the articles on |hהַצַּדִּיק|h* and |hהָרְשָׁעִֽים|h* (see jm 137.l and NIDOTTE 3.752). Yahweh has acted in accordance with what he said (v 18).
\notfr (f) NOTE
\notsp (f) NOTE
\notpt (f) NOTE
\notxx (f) NOTE
\not (g) This appears to be unique, being the only instance of the term not referring to God or a human (cf TDOT, NIDOTTE), though note the similar concepts in Psa 119, where the noun |hצֶדֶק|h* is used as an attribute of God's statutes.
\notfr (g) NOTE
\notsp (g) NOTE
\notpt (g) NOTE
\notxx (g) NOTE
\not (h) On the basis of Phoenician inscriptions and Ugaritic texts, the theological dictionaries (TDOT, TLOT, NIDOTTE) and more recent commentaries (WBC, NICOT) argue for 'legitimate descendant' here and in 33:15. However, even the more recent translations do not follow them.
\notfr (h) NOTE
\notsp (h) NOTE
\notpt (h) NOTE
\notxx (h) NOTE
\not (i) The commentaries (WBC, TOTC, KD) understand a reference to a king who will exercise justice, whereas most of the translations render it by 'triumphant' or 'victorious' or the like. However, the latter stretches the meaning too far and it is not necessary to assume that it has the same meaning as the participle that follows, so KTBH follows the commentaries.
