\keyverse TEV - Then you will be pleased with |bproper |b*sacrifices and with our burnt offerings; and bulls will be sacrificed on your altar
\eval There is a variety of translations for this verse reflecting the interpretations discussed in the Comments. TEV and CEV take a similar view to KTBH and REB 'appointed' is close. Some render by 'righteous, right' (NIV, RSV, NRS), which avoids commitment to any one interpretation.
\ref %!A!3%" 3!$!&"" 3!S!5#"
\paradigc 
\not (a) Or possibly 'paths where I experience his covenant faithfulness' (cf NJB 'paths of saving justice'). This fits well with the shepherd-sheep imagery, but is not widely accepted.
\notfr (a) NOTE
\notsp (a) NOTE
\notpt (a) NOTE
\notxx (a) NOTE
\not (b) Verse 20 would suggest the genitive is 'the gates for the righteous',  through which they enter. 'Those entering in must be "righteous ones;" only conformity with the divine loving will gives the right to enter' (KD, cf TLOT).
\notfr (b) NOTE
\notsp (b) NOTE
\notpt (b) NOTE
\notxx (b) NOTE
\not (c) The context seems to demand a reference to Israel's righteous behaviour. However, the parallel expression is 'the glory of Yahweh'. NICOT notes that 'the two ideas are combined. It is as the Lord empowers the people in his gracious righteousness that they will be enabled to live righteous and holy lives in his presence.' Nonetheless, the focus seems to be on Israel's righteous behaviour.
\notfr (c) NOTE
\notsp (c) NOTE
\notpt (c) NOTE
\notxx (c) NOTE
\not (d) The Masoretic accents indicate that the phrase |hנְוֵה־צֶדֶק|h* is in apposition to |hיהוה|h* (cf WBC), and the same phrase is used in 50:7 to refer to Yahweh himself. However, none of the standard translations takes it this way. Rather, |hנְוֵה־צֶדֶק|h* and הַר הַקֹּדֶשׁ are taken in apposition to one another as a vocative, referring to Zion. In this case, the meaning of the phrase is 'the place where people live righteously'.
\notfr (d) NOTE
\notsp (d) NOTE
\notpt (d) NOTE
\notxx (d) NOTE
\not (e) Most translations render |hצֶדֶק|h* by 'just cause' or the like, but the psalmist is clearly confident of the righteousness of his behaviour, so it must be his status as a righteous person that is in question. WBC notes that '|hצֶדֶק|h* causes problems, though the parallelism implies that it must mean something like "(plea for) vindication, righteousness."' Similarly TOTC, '[the psalmist] searches his heart and finds assurance that his piety is not pretence ... he therefore appeals to God to adjudicate accordingly, for his name needs to be cleared'.
\notfr (e) NOTE
\notsp (e) NOTE
\notpt (e) NOTE
\notxx (e) NOTE
\not (f) The use of |hשׁלם|h* 'to restore, replace' (HALOT) and the promise of increase in the next verse seem to require a focus on the well-being that would result from the righteous behaviour to which Bildad is urging Job. Compare NICOT, 'your righteous estate .... means that the extensive holdings of Job bore witness to the righteousness of their sheikh', though WBC disagrees, 'the righteousness of Job is regarded poetically as inhabiting his "estate"' and translates 'the abode of your righteousness.'
\notfr (f) NOTE
\notsp (f) NOTE
\notpt (f) NOTE
\notxx (f) NOTE
\not (g) The suffix refers to the psalmist, but the |hצֶדֶק|h* appears to be salvation wrought by Yahweh. In v 27b, the psalmist's friends respond with praise to Yahweh, and in v 28 the psalmist's own response is to speak of Yahweh's |hצֶדֶק|h*. In other words, the suffix is not subjective, but expresses the beneficiary.
\notfr (g) NOTE
\notsp (g) NOTE
\notpt (g) NOTE
\notxx (g) NOTE
\not (h) There is no suffix in this verse, but see the next verse.
\notfr (h) NOTE
\notsp (h) NOTE
\notpt (h) NOTE
\notxx (h) NOTE
\not (i) Oaks, planted by Yahweh that display his splendour, his faithfulness to his covenant. That is not to imply that the people do not behave righteously, but that the focus is on their restoration. Compare NICOT, 'as they live they show the righteousness of God (cf. 1:27), which is both his grace to save and his power to enable righteous living.'
\notfr (i) NOTE
\notsp (i) NOTE
\notpt (i) NOTE
\notxx (i) NOTE
\not (j) The suffix refers to Zion, but it appears to be salvation wrought by Yahweh and displayed to the nations as in 61:3. In other words, the suffix is not subjective, but expresses the beneficiary.
\notfr (j) NOTE
\notsp (j) NOTE
\notpt (j) NOTE
\notxx (j) NOTE
\not (k) The phrase |hנְוֵה־צֶדֶק|h* (cf Job 8:6; Jer 31:23) is in apposition to Yahweh and |hנָוֶה|h* continues the imagery of the flock and |hרֵבֶץ|h* 'resting-place' in v 6. This much is clear. Many translations render the phrase by 'their true pasture' of the like, but, though this makes good sense in the context, to stretch the meaning of |hצֶדֶק|h* so that it comes to mean 'true' as opposed to 'false' goes too far. The assignment follows KD, 'the One in whom is contained that righteousness which is the source of Israel's salvation'.
\notfr (k) NOTE
\notsp (k) NOTE
\notpt (k) NOTE
\notxx (k) NOTE
\not (l) It is possible that this refers to God's original intention, when he gave |hתּוֹרָה|h* to Israel, to fulfil the covenant blessings, but v 20 refers to Israel's blindness and v 22 to the covenant curses which Yahweh has brought on Israel. The context thus seems to point to Yahweh's righteousness as his fulfilling of the covenant curses on unfaithful Israel.
\notfr (l) NOTE
\notsp (l) NOTE
\notpt (l) NOTE
\notxx (l) NOTE
\not (m) Although the covenant is not prominent in the wisdom literature, God's activities in vv 5-7 do correspond well to his acts of covenant righteousness.
\notfr (m) NOTE
\notsp (m) NOTE
\notpt (m) NOTE
\notxx (m) NOTE
\not (n) The form is unusual, either with reduced vowels because of the maqqeph (BDB) or mispointed (NIDOTTE), but the meaning is fairly certain.
\notfr (n) NOTE
\notsp (n) NOTE
\notpt (n) NOTE
\notxx (n) NOTE
