\not (a) This assignment understands the 3fs suffix on |hחשׁב |h*to refer to a preceding verbal idea (GKC 135.p), in this case, Abram's faith, and follows NIDOTTE in seeing this faith counted as a righteous act. The covenant in view is the Abrahamic, rather than the Sinaitic, so this is a unique instance of this Contextual Use.
\notfr (a) NOTE
\notsp (a) NOTE
\notpt (a) NOTE
\notxx (a) NOTE
\not (b) Note the parallel to Yahweh's |hצְדָקָה|h*. The Israelites were faithful to the covenant by driving out the invaders.
\notfr (b) NOTE
\notsp (b) NOTE
\notpt (b) NOTE
\notxx (b) NOTE
\not (c) The assignment assumes that Yahweh loves righteousness done by others, rather than that he loves to do righteousness (contrast Psa 33:5). Note the chiastic arrangement in 11:5-7: righteous, wicked, wicked, righteous.
\notfr (c) NOTE
\notsp (c) NOTE
\notpt (c) NOTE
\notxx (c) NOTE
\not (d) Note the irony: 'Now I shall expose your conduct that you think so righteous' (REB89).
\notfr (d) NOTE
\notsp (d) NOTE
\notpt (d) NOTE
\notxx (d) NOTE
\not (e) The acts they thought righteous were clearly not.
\notfr (e) NOTE
\notsp (e) NOTE
\notpt (e) NOTE
\notxx (e) NOTE
\not (f) Commentators are divided over whether מַגִּישֵׁי מִנְחָה בִּצְדָקָה refers to those who would offer sacrifices according to the law, in contrast to those being offered in Malachi's time, or sacrifices offered by those who were faithful to the law. In an eschatological context, the purification by the refiner will be radical and the Levites will have a thoroughgoing righteousness. As a result, of course, the sacrifices they offer will be as prescribed by the law, but the primary reference of |hצְדָקָה|h* is to that of the offerers, not their offerings.
\notfr (f) NOTE
\notsp (f) NOTE
\notpt (f) NOTE
\notxx (f) NOTE
\not (g) There are three possibilities distinguished by the way the Hiphil of |hשׁוב|h* is understood.1. 'He [God] restores to a person his righteous status' (cf NIV).2. 'He [the man] recounts to [other] people his salvation' (cf RSV).3. 'He [God] repays him for his righteous behaviour' (cf NRS).The third option seems unlikely in view of the confession of unrighteousness in v 27-28. The second is sometimes based on emendation of |hוישׁב |h*to |hויבשׂר|h*, but the Hiphil of |hשׁוב|h*, even without a speech word can have the sense 'bring back word, report' (BDB 999b) and this would fit well with the |hתְּרוּעָה|h* in the preceding colon. However, this would require the |hאֱנוֹשׁ|h* to refer not to the restored sinner but collectively to people not otherwise mentioned; this seems unnatural. Thus KTBH follows option 1.
\notfr (g) NOTE
\notsp (g) NOTE
\notpt (g) NOTE
\notxx (g) NOTE
\not (h) This second occurrence of |hצְדָקָה |h*in the verse is omitted by LXX and some mss of Vul. Some modern translations (RSV, NRS) and commentators (WBC) follow this, but the word is retained by HOTTP. It should probably be retained, recognised as a word-play (cf NICOT) and seen to have a meaning different from the first occurrence. Most translations that retain it, render it by 'prosperity' or the like, and this fits well with its parallels, |hחַי|h* and |hכָּבוֹד|h*.
\notfr (h) NOTE
\notsp (h) NOTE
\notpt (h) NOTE
\notxx (h) NOTE
\not (i) There is general agreement that the king in view is Yahweh himself, and that this is not an intrusion of a reference to the earthly king. See the commentaries.
\notfr (i) NOTE
\notsp (i) NOTE
\notpt (i) NOTE
\notxx (i) NOTE
\not (j) |hצְדָקָה|h* may be an attribute of the city, but the context is one of deliverance and restoration, so it is better to take it as a reference to God's righteousness when he acts on behalf of a faithful, or in this case repentant, people.
\notfr (j) NOTE
\notsp (j) NOTE
\notpt (j) NOTE
\notxx (j) NOTE
\not (k) This assignment is debatable; the issue is whether vv 9-11 continue the confession of sin or represent an appeal to God for his saving |hמִשְׁפָּט|h* and |hצְדָקָה|h*. If 9a and 11b form an |iinclusio|i*, as Motyer notes (1993: 486), then |hיְשׁוּעָה|h* in v 11 points towards the latter.
\notfr (k) NOTE
\notsp (k) NOTE
\notpt (k) NOTE
\notxx (k) NOTE
\not (l) The assignment assumes that Yahweh loves to do righteousness, rather than that he loves righteousness done by others (contrast Psa 11:7). All the other attributes in vv 4-5 are God's. The context seems to be the whole of creation rather than the narrower covenant relationship with Israel.
\notfr (l) NOTE
\notsp (l) NOTE
\notpt (l) NOTE
\notxx (l) NOTE
\not (m) The suffix refers to God, so it is God's righteousness that is in view, but it is the king who is to exercise it (v 2), so this instance of the term is assumed to have a human as the main participant.
\notfr (m) NOTE
\notsp (m) NOTE
\notpt (m) NOTE
\notxx (m) NOTE
\not (n) On the basis of Phoenician inscriptions and Ugaritic texts, the theological dictionaries (TDOT, TLOT, NIDOTTE) and more recent commentaries (WBC, NICOT) argue for 'legitimate descendant' here and in 23:5. However, even the more recent translations do not follow them.
\notfr (n) NOTE
\notsp (n) NOTE
\notpt (n) NOTE
\notxx (n) NOTE
\not (o) There is general agreement that |hצְדָקָה|h* here refers to a legal right to receive anything from David, though it could be translated 'what right status do I still have to appeal'.
\notfr (o) NOTE
\notsp (o) NOTE
\notpt (o) NOTE
\notxx (o) NOTE
\not (p) There is general agreement that |hצְדָקָה|h* here refers to a legal right or authority to participate or interfere in what Nehemiah was doing. Although Sanballat was later governor of Samaria, Nehemiah's official credentials (2:9) established his authority.
\notfr (p) NOTE
\notsp (p) NOTE
\notpt (p) NOTE
\notxx (p) NOTE
\not (q) This is used elsewhere as a cultic term and may refer to their having no right in the cultic practices in Jerusalem (NICOT).
\notfr (q) NOTE
\notsp (q) NOTE
\notpt (q) NOTE
\notxx (q) NOTE
