\heb מְזִמָּה
\strong 4209
\pos ncf
\gloss plan, scheme; resourcefulness
\freq 19
\sub זמם
\intro The meaning of this word can be defined as 'Plan or strategy that someone has thought out to accomplish a well-defined goal'. From 'plan' there is an extension of meaning to 'the |iability|i* of planning'. The word sometimes occurs in the negative sense of 'plotting', 'scheming' but this is not part of the lexical meaning.
\hebraist See Fox, M.V. 1993 "Words for Wisdom." |iZeitschrift für Althebraistik |i*6: 149-169.
\dfnotes |hמְזִמָּה|h* is part of the Wisdom frame. The mental skill (that can be acquired) is not traditional knowledge but a personal initiative: thinking out a strategy or plan in order to achieve a goal. In wisdom literature, where the son is taught to find his way into the world, |hמְזִמָּה|h* is valued quite positively. But otherwise |hמְזִמָּה|h* features in contexts where the Agents start to look primarily after their own objectives, which results in 'scheming' which damages other people. Perhaps  |hמְזִמָּה|h* is less positively valued in cultures where private enterprise is less appreciated. A culture that is tradition-centered will not favour innovative enterprises.
\addinfo The noun |hמְזִמָּה|h* is linked with |hחשׁב |h*'to think, plan' and its derivatives several times, which indicates that we are dealing with a mental activity. Likewise, it is often juxtaposed with verbs like |hעשׂה|h* ' to do, make' and |hיכל|h* 'to succeed' which indicates that what is lacking from |hמְזִמָּה|h* is the execution of the plans.Just as with |hזמם|h* 'to plan, plot', negative connotations are part of the context, not necessarily central to the noun |hמְזִמָּה|h* itself (see, e.g., Job 21:27, where it is conveyed by the verb |hחמס|h* 'to plot violence', and the article by Fox). It is notable, however, that the plural |hמְזִמֹּות|h* is limited to instances where a negative frame (damage to others) is invoked (Pro 14:17; Psa 139:20). But here the logical extension of meaning is that a 'man of plans' (Fox: '... private thoughts') is not, as in the Western world, an enterprising fellow who is bound for success, but a schemer, so that the pejorative connotation has often become part of the plural of this noun.
