\heb חָכְמָה
\strong 2451
\pos ncf
\gloss wisdom, skill
\freq 153
\sub חכם. חָכָם
\intro 1. The Meanings of this word are all related to a central meaning, 'wisdom', 'expertise'.2. The Hebrew concept of 'wisdom, expertise' is wider than the Western idea of wisdom (see Domain and Frame Notes).3. With respect to crafts, it denotes skill in a profession (Meaning 1a).4. With respect to all other kinds of tasks in life, it denotes wisdom, insight and prudence (Meaning 1b).5. 'Wisdom' is also the name of a Lady, who personifies wisdom and the desire to make foolish people wise (Meaning 2).
\comp 1. Frame: Wisdom    a. Specific Frame: Skill; Contextual Domain: Crafts     b. Specific Frame: -- ; Contextual Domains: numerous2. Frame: Instruction; Intrinsic Domain: Personification (of Meaning 1b).
\dfnotes The Hebrew root חכם 'to be wise' and its derivatives can serve as a good heading for the Wisdom frame, for it encompasses all other terms related to wisdom. At first sight, its translation does not seem to pose grave problems. Relevant dictionary entries are often quite straightforward and modern versions are almost unanimous in their use of '(to be) wise' and 'wisdom' as its renderings. Most of the secondary literature does not deal with the semantic or cultural meanings, but with the socio-cultural setting of the Wisdom tradition, its international character, its development throughout Wisdom literature etc. The standard rendering חכם = 'wise' may be an attractive and often quite adequate choice, which mirrors the conceptual unity of the Old Testament. Nevertheless, we should be aware of different connotations of wisdom between ancient Israel and the modern Western world, to which many scholars and dictionary writers belong. A scholar that does express sensitivity to the differences is M.V. Fox in his |iProverbs 1-9|i* (Anchor Bible Commentary), New York 2000, 29, 32ff. He defines חָכְמָה as 'a high degree of knowledge and skill in any domain' and thus allows a much wider sense for the Hebrew term than its English counterpart 'wisdom' usually has. He suggests that English 'tends to distinguish, perhaps too sharply, between knowledge and intelligence' (32). There are two important differences between the Hebrew and English concepts of 'wisdom'.The first difference is the following. In both Hebrew and English phraseology, wisdom is believed to be located in the 'heart'. But it is important to remind ourselves that the concept 'heart' fulfills different functions in ancient Israelite and modern Western thought. In English, the concept 'heart' is the seat of the emotions, notably love, with which it is symbolically associated. In Hebrew thinking, לֵב 'heart' is the centre of the will and of the rational faculties. Often לֵב can be translated as 'mind' or 'brain'. The חָכְמָה 'wisdom'-activities of the Hebrew 'heart' would be referred to in English as 'intelligence', in the widest sense of the word (comprising both IQ and EQ [Emotional Intelligence]). Emotional Intelligence, as is it conceived in the West, is a fruitful interaction between emotions and rational faculties, resulting in 'emotional management', so that an emotionally intelligent person knows how to handle his own emotions, how to handle situations, how to use emotions for the best etc. In short, Emotional Intelligence equals the Western concept of 'wisdom'. Modern textbooks contrast Emotional Intelligence with professional expertise. A 'computer nerd' may be a good professional, but he is emotionally and socially handicapped. But the Hebrew term חָכְמָה covers both professional/rational and emotional/social expertise. Next to 'wisdom', 'expertise' would also be a good gloss for חָכְמָה. Judged from the modern Western perspective, the Book of Proverbs would not typically be called a treasure of wisdom. Modern critics have called it 'a collection of platitudes', and this (exaggerated) judgement does reflect some of the different attitudes towards wisdom then and now. In short, the Hebrew wisdom frame is much wider than its English counterpart. The former includes professional skill, rational faculties, usable for different purposes, interpersonal skills and, generally, the art of living.The second difference is that in English, 'wisdom' has positive overtones: wisdom is inherently 'good', to speakers of English. Using wisdom for bad purposes is considered something of an impossibility|i; |i*that would be called 'shrewdness' or 'cunning'. This is different in Hebrew, where חָכְמָה can definitely be used for evil purposes (2SA 13:3; JOB 5:13 etc.). Seen from this perspective, it becomes clearer why some Bible passages stress that wisdom equals 'righteousness'. For that was by no means clear to Israelites from their understanding of חָכְמָה. Also, that wisdom begins with the 'fear of the Lord'|i |i*had to be |iasserted|i*, it was clearly not taken for granted. The entire frame of חָכְמָה 'wisdom', as well as several sub-terms such as ערם, עָרְמָה, זמם, מְזִמָּה, thus has a more neutral and instrumental (i.e. usable for good and bad purposes) character than the English wisdom frame.
