\sub עול
\intro Ten of the 22 occurrences are found in Ezekiel and nine of these ten are in the three watchman passages (3:16-21; 18:1-32; 33:1-20), where it has a restricted sense. It is used there to describe the sin that a righteous person commits when he turns from his righteousness to commit various unrighteous acts. This meaning is illustrated in 18:26: |ibshuv-tsadiq mitsidqato ve'asa 'avel umet 'aleyhem b'avlo 'asher-'asa yamut|i*.Someone commits |i‘avel|i* when he treats others unfairly or dishonestly even though his position or role requires him to deal with them fairly and honestly. People living in a community that is largely law-abiding expect that a person who has been entrusted with a responsible role (such as a judge or a seller in the marketplace) will act in just and principled ways towards them. But in the case of |i‘avel|i*, though they deserve and expect justice, they find that the expected behaviour of a |itsadiq|i* (‘a righteous person’) has been abandoned and replaced by injustice and dishonesty. All occurrences of |i'avel|i* entail an unexpected distortion of the accepted standards of right and proper behaviour when dealing with other humans. They, therefore, result in a breach of trust between the agent of the injustice or dishonesty and its victim. The biblical occurrences can be sorted into three kinds of sin:1. Commercial dishonesty; unfair business practices (Lev 19:35; Deu 25:16; Ezk 28:18). 2. Courtroom injustice; unfairness in deciding legal cases (Lev 19:15; Ezk 18:8; Job 34:10; Psa 82:2).  3. Wrongful acts in general that involve a deliberate choice away from the expected righteous behaviour. A list of various sins is repeated three times in Ezekiel 18:5-19, where |i‘avel |i*is sometimes seen as a cover term for the whole list (eg Ezk 18:24). This broader meaning of |i'avel|i* may be used in protests of innocence, where the defendant, whether God (Deu 32:4; Jer 2:5) or some other righteous person (Psa 7:4; and Job 34:32) testifies that he has not abandoned his righteousness. Also included in this category are the remaining occurrences in Ezekiel (and possibly Psa 53:2 and Pro 29:27).[Residue: The kinds of sin referred to in Psalm 53:2 and Proverbs 29:27 are less clear from the context, but their contexts do not exclude them from any of the above. The occurrence in Ezekiel 18:8 is preceded by commercial dishonesty (specifically the charging of interest) and followed by courtroom injustice. But the lines remain balanced (with two clauses on each theme), if |i‘avel |i*relates to courtroom injustice rather than commercial dishonesty.]
\comp Uses 1a and 1b both involve improper financial gain at the expense of those who deserve a fair deal.
