\sub יוֹמָם
\comp The word is used to refer to particular days (Meanings 1 - 5) or to periods of days (Meaning 6). It is also used within discourse to evoke elapsed time and to locate an event in time (that is to say relative to other events which are unfolding) (Meanings 7 - 10). There can be some ambiguity between these two ways of categorising, for instance a particular day may also be a day in the unfolding of a discourse. We have tried to categorise on the basis of which is most prominent for each instance [see below for example]. Within Meanings 1 - 5, the entry can be seen as reflecting various aspects of dayness, referred to linguistically as perspectivisation. The word can also be used adverbially (Meaning 11) to attribute a 'daily-ness' (or other period of repetitiveness) to an activity, or adjectively (Meaning 12), for instance of an allotment appropriate to a day.Example of categorisation: Hosea 10:9 "Since the days of Gibeah, you have sinned...". This is an example of 'days' referring to (i) a period of time, to (ii) a significant event (in particular, a significant |inegative|i* event.) It could be categorised in one of those ways. However it is also an example of the time of one event (the heinous event invoked by 'Gibeah') being related to the time of another event ('sinning'). Since, in reality, Israelite sinning did not start with the event invoked by 'Gibeah', this event is being called to mind as a prominent event to show that Israelite sinning has been going on for a long time. We have therefore categorised it primarily as a 'discourse' use of 'day', since this seems to be the most prominent frame. The other two or three categories may appear as contextual domains.[examples][multiple categorisation]I Samuel 14:52 - All the days of Saul there was bitter war with the Philistines, and whenever Saul saw a mighty or brave man, he took him into his service.[life of ruler, time when, discourse role] - <life of ruler> as being more culturally cognitive could take priority[researcher's note] It may be appropriate to point out nominal and adjectival (eg. they were 'old') use.
