\sub חָכָם. חָכְמָה
\intro The Hebrew root |hחכם|h* has a more rational connotation than English ‘wise’, which is rather an affair of intuition. In Hebrew, wisdom is more linked to IQ than to EQ (Emotional Quotient), more to Rational Intelligence than to Emotional Intelligence. Under the related entry |hחָכְמָה|h* (Domain and frame notes) you will find an explanation of what this means.
\hebraist The references under the Meaning 'To make wise' have been taken together here, but there is a difference between Piel and Hiphil, however small. The Piel basically designates bringing about a state, referred to by the base root, or it designates bringing about the outcome of the action designated by the base root. The Piel thus causes a state rather than an action, which is the characteristic of the Hiphil.When applied to|h חכם|h*, this means that the Piel |hחִכֵּם |h*designates bringing about the state of being informed and/or the possession of relevant knowledge - perhaps even against the will of the Patient, whereas the Hiphil |hהֶחְכִּים |h*designates bringing about the event of being actively wise. This distinction fits well to the references listed below. The Torah makes those who study and observe it into men who are wise and who act wisely (Psa 19:8; 119:98, both Hiphil). On the other hand, animals have been made ‘wise’ in the sense of 'programmed for their particular task', not actively wise in the strict sense of the word (Pro 30:24, Pual=Passive Piel). The same holds true for the Egyptian officials, of whom it is said in a deprecatory way that they were 'made wise', i.e. instructed to obey Joseph for that moment (Psa 105:22, Piel). If the target language allows it, these distinctions should be reflected in translation.For further reading: B. K. Waltke & M. O'Connor, |iBiblical Hebrew Syntax|i*, Winona Lake 1990, par. 24. and 27.
