\heb כְּסִיל
\level1 1
\strong 3684
\gloss (Complacent) fool
\freq 75
\sub כסל
\intro 1. The word can function both as an adjective and as a noun.2. Characteristic of the כְּסִיל is stupidity combined with complacency. 3. The כְּסִיל does not see the harmful consequences of his actions, or does not care about them. 4. For the difference with אֱוִיל, see Comments for Hebraists.5. A separate Meaning (homonym) of כְּסִיל is 'Orion' (a constellation of stars).6. Another separate meaning (homonym) is a place name.
\hebraist According to most scholars, this word can be derived from a root meaning 'to be fat'. From this, its meaning gradually developed to 'to be slow' and 'to be stupid'. Following Fox's article, we could paraphrase the meaning of the noun כְּסִיל as follows: the כְּסִיל is someone who is not very clever, and shows too much satisfaction with who he is and what he does. He is so satisfied with himself that his judgement and his brain do not work well anymore. He does not see the harmful consequences of his rash words or his actions, and if he sees them, he does not care about them. In this way he, and other people with him, come to harm.The difference with אֱוִיל is difficult to draw, because the book of Proverbs ascribes similar behaviour to both כְּסִיל and אֱוִיל. Several scholars think it is not possible to make a distinction. However, it is hard to believe that two words have exactly the same meaning. Fox suggests a difference. According to him, the כְּסִיל 'complacent fool' does stupid and wrong things |ibecause |i*he is foolish and satisfied with himself, whereas the אֱוִיל is morally perverse, and this |imakes him do |i*foolish things. Fox finds it striking that the כְּסִיל is sometimes mentioned in one breath with someone who knows nothing (Psa 49:11; 92:7; 94:8). There is little hope of educating the כְּסִיל, but it is not impossible (Pro 8:5b), but there is nowhere any mention of improving an אֱוִיל. So its seems that the אֱוִיל is a hardened version of the כְּסִיל, for he despises wisdom (Pro 1:7), is incorrigible (Pro 27:22). It is also interesting that אֱוִיל and אִוֶּלֶת, in contrast to כְּסִיל, are sometimes contrasted with words like 'upright' and 'righteous'. The folly of the אֱוִיל goes to the extent that he is fond of doing evil. He does not make amends for what he has done (Pro 14:9). With respect to the connection of Folly terms and morality, we should note that how Israelites understood folly would be different from a modern Western analysis by virtue of their being a high-contact society. That is to say, people in the West would view 'folly' as more an individual thing - in the first place affecting or being to the detriment of the individual. Folly could concern immorality but not necessarily; it could simply be with money, for instance. In a high-contact society, such ancient Israel, but also many Asian and African societies of the present, 'folly' would be felt by the society. Folly is then, in a sense, an irresponsible behaviour towards the society and to the detriment of the society, in particular the immediate family. In this way, folly so can seen as 'immoral', because the ‘fool’ does not fulfil his proper role in society that a group mentality would require, where each member is expected to contribute to the societal good. One might do it by being 'simple', another by being 'lazy', another by being 'petulant'. Reference: Fox, M.V. 1997 "Words for Folly" |iZeitschrift für Althebraistik |i*10:4-15; B. Waltke, |iProverbs|i* (NICOT), section (3), 'Two Words for Fool'.This word occurs also 5x in Ben Sira.
\comp 1. Frame: Folly; Experiencer: human   1.a. adjective   1.b noun2. Frame: Astronomy3. Frame: Topography
