\eval The precise translation of this verse is much in debate (see |iTranslator's Handbook|i*, TWAT III, 495 and commentaries on this passage). Some scholars think that the expression דַּעַת טוֹב וָרַע 'knowledge of good and evil', refers to 'knowledge of what is useful or useless for mankind'. That results in a very different translation from 'practical experience of good and evil', or 'knowledge of everything' (whereby 'good and evil' are taken as a summary of totality). In KTBH, 'knowledge of good and evil' is taken as practical experience with the essence of good and evil, and their consequences. But this practical experience does not necessarily mean being personally involved in doing good and evil, because the expression is also used for God (Gen 3:5, 22).Most English versions have 'knowledge of good and evil', which seems pretty general. This has the advantage of not making too clear a choice of what it entails. The CEV (also TEV) rendering ('the other tree... gave the power to know the difference between good and wrong') implies a much clearer choice, but this excludes other interpretations.
