\heb מַחֲשָׁבָה
\strong 4284
\alt מַחֲשֶׁבֶת
\pos ncf
\gloss design, plan
\freq 56
\intro Although this noun has long been rendered as 'thought' in older versions, it has nothing to do with abstract thinking or philosophy, but rather with practical thinking towards a purpose . It has two Meanings. The first Meaning is 'design', i.e. the result of the imaginative practical thinking of an artist or technician. The second Meaning is 'plan', i.e. practical thinking to put intentions into practice (often bad ones) in the future. The difference of this second Meaning with |hמְזִמָּה|h* is that the latter is more concrete.
\comp 1. Agent: human; patient: inanimate, implicit2. Agent: human, God; patient: event, inanimate, implicit; benefactive: human, implicit
\dfnotes The noun מַחֲשָׁבָה belongs to the Wisdom frame (see also חשׁב, Domain and frame notes)‏. Designs or plans originate in the 'heart' (Gen 6:5; Psa 33:11; Pro 19:21; 6:18; Jer 4:14; 18:12)‏, i.e. in the centre of the rational faculties (English: 'brain')‏. This is because in Hebrew, wisdom is rather intellectual than intuitive (see חָכְמָה, Domain and frame notes)‏. In Israelite society, traditional wisdom was highly valued. It seems that private initiative for one's own benefit was not appreciated, because pursuing one's own private interests is often not good for the community as a whole. 'A "man of plans" is not, as in the Western world, an enterprising fellow who is bound for success, but a schemer' (quote from Domain and Frame notes under מְזִמָּה)‏. It is, therefore, no coincidence, that the noun מַחֲשָׁבָה is often mentioned in one breath with רַע, רָעָה or אָוֶן, all meaning 'evil', sometimes even as near synonyms (Est 8:3; Jer 18:11)‏. So it comes that in Jer 29:11, Yhwh says that He has plans for his people, but immediately adds that these plans are not bad, but good.
\addinfo This word occurs 6x in singular and 50x in plural. In the technical/artistic meaning, singular and plural occur equally often, but the meaning 'plan' occurs almost always in plural. This does not necessarily mean that the text speaks of more than one plan. It may also mean that the mind is thinking |iall the time|i* about its plan or goal, so that the activity is viewed not as a single occurrence, but as a series of activities of the mind.
